<section class="intro-section mb-12">
    <h3 id="mission">Mission</h3>
    <p>
        <strong>Web Routing</strong> brings the routing domain into the platform on the same terms as every
        other Web Everything standard: a route table is declared by its <em>semantic intent</em> &mdash; the
        URL patterns, their guards, loaders and nested outlets &mdash; kept strictly separate from how a router
        runtime commits navigations. Routing was, until now, <strong>partly built but ownerless</strong>: the
        <a href="/intents/navigation/">Navigation Intent</a> owns the user-perceivable UX axes
        (<code>structure / history / scroll / transition / guard / persistence</code>), the <code>router</code>
        block (<code>we:src/_data/blocks/router.json</code>, <code>implementedBy: @frontierui/blocks/router</code>)
        is the imperative runtime, and <a href="/projects/webguards/">Web Guards</a> treats a route guard as one
        instance of its predicate seam &mdash; but <em>nothing</em> owned route <em>format</em> as a declarable
        contract, the URL as a shared state store, technical routing config, or sitemap derivation. This project
        is that owner. Per the constellation rule the contract lives here in <code>@webeverything</code>, the
        runtime stays in Frontier UI, and the UX stays in the Navigation Intent.
    </p>
</section>

<section id="scope" class="section-card">
    <h3 id="scope-heading">Scope</h3>
    <p>
        The load-bearing surface is not route format alone but <strong>the URL as a state store many stateful
        components read and write</strong> &mdash; a data-grid's filters / sort / page, a tab selection, a
        wizard step, a disclosure's open-state. The hard constraint (ratified 2026-06-23): <strong>nothing is
        forced</strong>. Whether any given state slice lives in the URL is a <em>per-slice dimension</em> with a
        permissive default, reusing the Navigation Intent's existing <code>persistence</code> vocabulary
        (<code>url | session | memory</code>) generalized from whole-view navigation down to each slice. The
        standard ships the mechanism and the vocabulary; it mandates no convention
        (<a href="/docs/agent/platform-decisions.md">conventions fold into compliance</a>). The shape is settled
        &mdash; ratified in
        <a href="/backlog/1685-webrouting-route-format-source-of-truth-declarative-dom-temp/">#1685</a> (codified
        at <a href="/docs/agent/platform-decisions.md">platform-decisions &sect; single-authoring-sot-derived-projection</a>)
        and scaffolded under epic
        <a href="/backlog/1684-scaffold-the-webrouting-standard-route-format-profile-url-as/">#1684</a>.
    </p>
    <div class="standards-grid">
        <div class="standard-card flex flex-col">
            <h4 id="scope-format" class="text-lg font-bold m-0 text-gray-900">Route-format profile</h4>
            <p class="text-gray-600 text-sm leading-relaxed mb-0">
                Declarative DOM is the authoring source-of-truth &mdash; <code>&lt;template route&gt;</code>
                children of <code>&lt;we-route-view&gt;</code>, with <strong>URLPattern</strong> as the pattern
                grammar &mdash; and webrouting <em>derives</em> a serializable route-map projection for non-DOM
                consumers. <span class="text-gray-400">(Schema + vectors in slice B,
                <a href="/backlog/1721-webrouting-serializable-route-map-projection-schema-conforma/">#1721</a>.)</span>
            </p>
        </div>
        <div class="standard-card flex flex-col">
            <h4 id="scope-url-state" class="text-lg font-bold m-0 text-gray-900">URL-as-state seam</h4>
            <p class="text-gray-600 text-sm leading-relaxed mb-0">
                The serialize / restore seam many stateful components share, with a per-slice
                <code>persistence</code> declaration grounded on the Navigation Intent's
                <code>url | session | memory</code> axis &mdash; <strong>never forced</strong>, permissive
                default. <span class="text-gray-400">(Shape decided in
                <a href="/backlog/1686-webrouting-url-as-state-seam-one-shared-serialize-sync-provi/">#1686</a>.)</span>
            </p>
        </div>
        <div class="standard-card flex flex-col">
            <h4 id="scope-sitemap" class="text-lg font-bold m-0 text-gray-900">Sitemap derivation</h4>
            <p class="text-gray-600 text-sm leading-relaxed mb-0">
                A v1 emitter set derived from the route table &mdash; the first real consumer of the serializable
                route-map projection, reading routes without instantiating the running app.
                <span class="text-gray-400">(Scope in
                <a href="/backlog/1688-webrouting-sitemap-derivation-scope-which-artifact-set-ships/">#1688</a>;
                technical-config home in
                <a href="/backlog/1687-webrouting-technical-config-home-schema-in-webrouting-vs-a-p/">#1687</a>.)</span>
            </p>
        </div>
    </div>
    <div class="bg-blue-50 border-l-4 border-blue-400 p-3 mt-6 text-xs text-blue-800">
        <strong>Status:</strong> concept &mdash; this is the project skeleton (slice A of epic
        <a href="/backlog/1684-scaffold-the-webrouting-standard-route-format-profile-url-as/">#1684</a>). The
        route-format profile, the URL-as-state contract, the sitemap deriver, and the technical-config home land
        in the following slices. Per the constellation rule the contract lives here in
        <code>@webeverything</code> and the router runtime ships in Frontier UI.
